title: fix: increase topLayer z-index to support up to 20 PCB layers
description: Fixes issue where layers would disappear with 8 layer PCBs by increasing topLayer z-index from 10 to 20, preventing negative z-indexes for multiple PCB layers.
body:
- Increased topLayer from 10 to 20 to prevent negative z-indexes
- Adjusted overlay z-indexes proportionally to stay above PCB layers
- Added 10-layer test fixture to verify layer visibility
- Fixes issue where layers would disappear with 8+ layer PCBs

I identified that the topLayer value in z-index-map.ts was set to 10, which was too low for PCBs with many layers. The z-index calculation formula topLayer - (order.length - i) would produce negative z-indexes when you have more than 10 layers in the rendering order, causing those layers to either not render or render incorrectly behind other elements. increased topLayer from 10 to 20 to support up to 20 layers without negative z-indexes, and also bumped up the other overlay z-indexes proportionally to ensure they stay above the PCB layers.

title: Fix multi-layer visibility issues: inner5,6 not showing and top layer…
description: Fixes visibility issues in an 8-layer PCB viewer where inner layers 5 and 6 were not displaying and the top layer disappeared when other layers were selected.
body:
https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/2460589c-7054-439b-abf3-870490fe9708


## Issue Summary
The 8-layer PCB viewer had two critical visibility problems: (1) inner layers 5 and 6 weren't displaying when viewing the top layer by default, and (2) the top layer would completely disappear when any other layer was selected. The root cause was threefold: a missing inner3 color mapping in LAYER_NAME_TO_COLOR, an incorrect DEFAULT_DRAW_ORDER that placed inner layers at the end causing them to render with the lowest z-index values, and a flawed orderAndFadeLayers() function that positioned the selected foreground layer early in the rendering order instead of on top.

## Changes Made
I fixed the color mapping by adding the missing inner3 entry, reordered DEFAULT_DRAW_ORDER to properly stack layers from bottom-to-top (board → inner6 through inner1 → bottom → top), and restructured orderAndFadeLayers() to place the foreground layer at the end of the order array so it always receives the highest z-index. I also added proper TypeScript typing to the eight-layer fixture and created a new overlapping-layers-test fixture with all pads at the same position to visually verify that the selected layer always appears on top with full opacity while other layers remain visible at 50% opacity beneath it. These changes ensure all 8 layers are visible and the selected layer always has the highest z-index for proper stacking behavior.

## New Files Created
eight-layer-circuit.fixture.tsx: This fixture was created to properly test the maximum 8-layer PCB configuration with correct TypeScript typing using AnyCircuitElement[]. It places one pad per layer side-by-side to verify that all layers (top, inner1-6, bottom) are visible in the layer dropdown and render correctly when selected individually or when viewing the top layer by default.

overlapping-layers-test.fixture.tsx: This specialized test fixture was created to definitively verify the z-index stacking fix by placing all 8 layers' pads at the exact same position (0, 0) with decreasing sizes, creating a visual "bullseye" effect. This makes it immediately obvious which layer is rendered on top when selected, allowing developers to quickly verify that the selected layer always appears fully opaque with the highest z-index while all other layers remain visible at 50% opacity beneath it.



fixes #398

title: Fix: Ensure drill and foreground layers render on top
description: Fixes rendering order to ensure drill and foreground layers consistently appear on top by simplifying z-index management in the orderAndFadeLayers method.
body: Refactored the orderAndFadeLayers method to simplify layer z-index management and ensure correct rendering order. Previously, zIndex was calculated using complex conditional logic. This has been simplified to derive the zIndex directly from the layer's position in the order array. The foreground layer, its associated silkscreen, and the drill layer are now consistently moved to the end of the rendering order to ensure they always appear on top.

This pull request introduces a new showErrorsInTextOverlay option to all major SVG conversion functions.             

 • When showErrorsInTextOverlay is set to true, any elements in the circuit JSON with a type ending in _error will   
   have their message rendered as a text overlay in the top-left corner of the SVG. This is useful for debugging     
   rendering issues or viewing validation errors directly on the visual output.                                      
 • The logic for creating the error overlay has been refactored into a new reusable utility, createErrorTextOverlay. 
 • This feature is implemented for the following SVG types:                                                          
    • PCB                                                                                                            
    • Schematic                                                                                                      
    • Assembly                                                                                                       
    • Pinout                                                                                                         
    • Solder Paste Mask                                                                                              
    • Schematic Simulation                                                                                           
 • New visual snapshot tests have been added to cover all affected SVG converters and ensure the error text is       
   rendered correctly. The test fixture now includes a component and simulation data for more comprehensive          
   snapshots.

title: refactor(pcb): Improve panel rendering and refactor numeric parsing
description: Adds support for rendering multi-board panels, refactors numeric parsing to use distance.parse, and fixes a bug in bounds calculation for polygon pads.
body:
This pull request introduces support for rendering multi-board panels, refactors numeric       
parsing to use distance.parse, and fixes a related bug in bounds calculation.                  

Key Changes:                                                                                   

 1 Multi-Board Panel Support:                                                                  
    • The SVG bounding box calculation in both PCB and solder paste mask renderers now         
      correctly includes pcb_panel elements, allowing panels with multiple boards to be        
      rendered properly.                                                                       
    • pcb_panel is no longer considered a board for board-specific boundary calculations, which
      improves logical consistency.                                                            
    • A new test case and snapshot have been added to verify the visual output of a multi-board
      panel.                                                                                   
 2 Refactor to distance.parse:                                                                 
    • The custom toNumeric helper function has been completely removed.                        
    • All numeric parsing of distance values now uses distance.parse from the circuit-json     
      library. This standardizes how distance units are handled and reduces maintenance.       
 3 Bug Fix:                                                                                    
    • Fixed a crash that occurred when calculating the bounds for pcb_smtpad elements with a   
      polygon shape. The bounds calculation logic was reordered to handle polygon pads         
      correctly, preventing an error from distance.parse receiving NaN values.

## Add PNG Snapshot Tests with Custom Font Rendering

This PR introduces PNG snapshot tests that render actual text using the TscircuitAlphabet.ttf font file, validating that the built font works correctly.

### What's New

**PNG Snapshot Tests** - 7 separate test files that render text using the actual TTF font:

1. **`tests/font-uppercase.test.ts`** - Renders all uppercase letters (A-Z) to verify capital letter rendering
2. **`tests/font-lowercase.test.ts`** - Renders all lowercase letters (a-z) to verify lowercase rendering
3. **`tests/font-numbers.test.ts`** - Renders digits 0-9 to verify number rendering
4. **`tests/font-punctuation.test.ts`** - Renders punctuation and symbols (.,*()-+=_[]<>'\"/\\) to verify special character rendering
5. **`tests/font-hello-world.test.ts`** - Renders "Hello World!" to verify common phrase rendering
6. **`tests/font-mixed-case.test.ts`** - Renders "The Quick Brown Fox 123" to verify mixed case and numbers together
7. **`tests/font-all-characters.test.ts`** - Renders a 4-line grid showing all character sets together for comprehensive visual verification

**Helper Module**
- `tests/helpers/render-text-to-png.ts` - Shared utility that uses `@resvg/resvg-js` to render SVG text with the custom font to PNG images

### Why This Matters

These tests validate the **final font product** (the .ttf file) rather than just the source SVG paths. If there's a bug in the font building process (like coordinate scaling issues), these PNG snapshots will catch it visually.

### Technical Details

- Uses `@resvg/resvg-js` to render SVG with custom font support
- Automatically wraps long text across multiple lines based on actual monospace width (1.392 * fontSize)
- Padding set to 0.9 * fontSize for optimal spacing
- All PNGs saved to `tests/__snapshots__/` directory

### Font Changes

**Note:** Updated `STROKE_WIDTH` from `0.16` to `0.12` in `scripts/build-font.ts` for better character visibility. The TscircuitAlphabet.ttf file has been rebuilt with this new stroke width.

### Dependencies

Added `@resvg/resvg-js` as a dev dependency for PNG rendering with custom font support.

## The Root Cause

  The issue was that typing in the bug report textarea was causing the entire FileMenuLeftHeader
  to re-render because:
  1. useBugReportDialog had state that changed on every keystroke (userText)
  2. This hook was called inside FileMenuLeftHeader
  3. Every state change triggered a re-render of the entire component tree

## Approach

Switch to uncontrolled input

body:
ref: https://github.com/tscircuit/schematic-trace-solver/issues/87#issuecomment-3463136963

We had a subsolver step, which was responsible for **removing redundant angles in the schematic trace**. I am just moving out to **run globally**. This fixes it a lot, but I'm not claiming this because the fix is non-standard. 

After this, I would look inside the _TraceOverlapShiftSolver_ to see if I could improve that! I feel a mix of both of them will be great and solve the issue best

description: This pull request addresses an issue where the reference text in the KiCad PCB was being skipped when converting to the circuit JSON format. The change ensures that the reference is included in the output, which is crucial for accurate representation of the PCB design.

title: chore: format the whole codebase
description: This pull request reformats the entire codebase to ensure consistent styling and adherence to coding standards. It includes changes to various files, primarily focusing on code formatting, such as spacing, line breaks, and consistent use of quotes. Additionally, it introduces a new GitHub Actions workflow for format checking on pushes and pull requests to the main branch.

title: fix: support kicad_pcb files which support uuid under the `tstamp`
description: This pull request introduces support for KiCad PCB files that utilize UUIDs under the tstamp field. The changes ensure that if a footprint does not have a UUID, the tstamp value will be used instead. This is crucial for maintaining compatibility with various PCB designs that may not conform to the expected UUID structure. Additionally, the changes include adjustments to how pad layers are determined and how pads are processed, ensuring that the system can handle both raw arrays and KiCad layer objects effectively.
